  "prompt": "In what grade do American students learn topics like integral, derivatives, organic chemistry, and waves in detail?",
  "response": "In the United States, the learning of topics such as integrals and derivatives, organic chemistry, and waves typically occurs at different educational levels:\n\n1. **Calculus (integrals and derivatives)**: Most students encounter calculus in high school, usually in 11th or 12th grade, during a course labeled \"Calculus\" or \"Advanced Placement (AP) Calculus.\" Some advanced students may take calculus as early as 10th grade if they are on an accelerated math track.\n\n2. **Organic Chemistry**: This subject is generally introduced in college-level courses. High school students interested in chemistry may take AP Chemistry in 11th or 12th grade, which covers general chemistry principles. Organic chemistry is typically a first-year college course, often taken by students pursuing degrees in sciences, health, or engineering.\n\n3. **Waves**: The topic of waves is usually introduced in high school physics courses, typically in 11th grade. Students may study sound waves, light waves, and other types of waves as part of a general physics curriculum or within a more advanced course.\n\nThese subjects can vary based on school curriculum and student progression, but generally, calculus is found in late high school, organic chemistry is in college, and waves are covered in high school physics classes.",
